1.) what are the errors it gave you? I would recommend using the rust method of running subtensor. Or even better I recommend connecting to subvortex and not messing around with running subtensor locally if you can’t figure it out. To use subvortex simply use `—subtensor.network subvortex.info:9944` you would input this flag in the pm2 start miner proccess. 

2.) no you don’t need to modify the docker .yml. 

3.) UFW is always recommended when dealing with external connections to your system, though it’s not absolutely necessary. UFW and PM2 however are not related, PM2 is a process manager and UFW is a networking tool. I have had some issues with servers where even after allowing ssh and ports I need to ssh into it still is unreachable. A process manager like PM2 is highly recommended, this allows the process to be managed and also run in the background, you could even disconnect from the server and it still runs. Very useful. 

4.) it really doesn’t matter, as long as you have the machine running the requirements and dependencies it shouldn’t matter what process you took to get there. You can use the readme of the GitHub or you can follow the newly updated gitbook docs at docs.neuralinternet.ai (reccomended)

The NVIDIA A100 80GB is generally more suitable than the L40S for AI workloads like pretraining, fine-tuning, and inference due to several key factors, particularly when considering cost, interconnect, and speed:

    •    A100 80GB has 80GB of HBM2e memory vs. 48GB GDDR6 on L40S.
    •    Higher VRAM allows larger batch sizes and enables pretraining/fine-tuning of larger models without requiring tensor/model parallelism, reducing communication overhead.
    •    HBM2e has much higher memory bandwidth (2TB/s vs. ~864GB/s on L40S), significantly improving training speed for large models.

2. Compute Performance (FP16/BF16/INT8)

Feature    A100 80GB    L40S
FP16 (TFLOPS)    ~78 TFLOPS    91 TFLOPS
BF16 (TFLOPS)    ~78 TFLOPS    91 TFLOPS
INT8 (TOPS)    ~624 TOPS    908 TOPS

    •    L40S has slightly higher raw compute power, but the A100’s HBM2e bandwidth ensures better real-world training performance.
    •    A100 is optimized for AI training, whereas L40S is tuned more for inference & rendering.

3. Interconnect and Scalability (NVLink & NVSwitch)
    •    A100 has 600GB/s NVLink interconnect, allowing multi-GPU training without being bottlenecked by PCIe.
    •    NVSwitch support in A100 nodes enables full bandwidth scaling across 8 GPUs, crucial for pretraining.
    •    L40S lacks NVSwitch and has only PCIe Gen4 (64GB/s), making multi-GPU training less efficient.

4. Cost and Power Efficiency
    •    L40S is cheaper (~$4K–$5K vs. A100 at ~$10K–$12K) and has lower power draw (300W vs. 400W).
    •    However, for large-scale AI training and fine-tuning, A100’s superior interconnect and memory bandwidth make it far more cost-efficient at scale.
    •    L40S is better suited for inferencing where cost savings per TFLOP matter more than memory bandwidth.

5. Real-World Use Cases
    •    A100 80GB is better for LLM pretraining (GPT, Llama, etc.), multi-GPU setups, and workloads requiring high memory bandwidth.
    •    L40S is best for inference workloads, model deployment, and vision tasks.

Conclusion

For pretraining and fine-tuning, the A100 80GB is the clear winner because:
    •    Higher VRAM & bandwidth reduce reliance on distributed training.
    •    NVLink & NVSwitch provide seamless multi-GPU scaling.
    •    Optimized for AI workloads (vs. L40S being more general-purpose).
